ATION -- tIII CONTRAST AND COMMONALITY: BYZANTINE MANUSCRIPTS -- t11 MEANING FROM THE MARGINS: GRAPHIC SIGNS, FRAMES AND INITIALS IN A NINTH-CENTURY BYZANTINE MANUSCRIPT -- t12 AN EXERCISE IN EXTRAVAGANCE AND ABUNDANCE: SOME THOUGHTS ON THE MARGINALIA DECORATA IN THE CODEX PARISINUS GRAECUS 216 -- t13 THE CROSS ON THE BOOK: DIAGRAM, ORNAMENT, MATERIALITY -- t14 GRAPHIC GLOSSES AND ARGUMENTATIVE ORNAMENT -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExaminations of the use of diagrams, symbols etc. found as commentary in medieval texts.In our electronic age, we are accustomed to the use of icons, symbols, graphs, charts, diagrams and visualisations as part of the vocabulary of communication. But this rich ecosystem is far from a modern phenomenon. Early medievalmanuscripts demonstrate that their makers and readers achieved very sophisticated levels of "graphicacy". When considered from this perspective, many elements familiar to students of manuscript decoration - embellished charactersin scripts, decorated initials, monograms, graphic symbols, assembly marks, diagrammatic structures, frames, symbolic ornaments, musical notation - are revealed to be not minor, incidental marks but crucial elements within the larger sign systems of manuscripts. This interdisciplinary volume is the first to discuss the conflation of text and image with a specific focus on the appearance of various graphic devices in manuscript culture. By looking attheir many forms as they appear from the fourth century to their full maturity in the long ninth century, its contributors demonstrate the importance of these symbols to understanding medieval culture. Michelle P. Brown FSA is Professor Emerita of Medieval Book History at the School of Advanced Study, University of London and was formerly the Curator of Illuminated Manuscripts at the British Library; Ildar Garipzanov is Professor of Early Medieval History at the Department of Archaeology, Conservation and History at the University of Oslo; Benjamin C. Tilghman is Assistant Professor of Art History at Washington College. Contributors: Tina Bawden, Michelle P.Brown, Leslie Brubaker, David Ganz, Ildar H. Garipzanov, Cynthia Hahn, Catherine E. Karkov, Herbert L. Kessler, Beatrice Kitzinger, Kallirroe Linardou, Lawrence Nees, Eric Palazzo, Benjamin C. Tilghman.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBook ornamentation. 0aGraphic arts. 0aIllumination of books and manuscripts, Medieval. 0aManuscripts, Medieval. 4aArt & Architecture. 4aBibliography & Manuscripts. 4aMedieval History. 7aART / European.2bisacsh  aanalysis.  aarchaeology.  aart history.  aart.  agraphic design.  ailluminated manuscripts.  aillustration.  aliterature.  amanuscripts.  amedieval culture.  amedieval text.  amuseum.  apreservation.  asymbols.  atext.1 aBawden, Tina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenjamin C. Tilghman, Benjamin C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrown, Michelle P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Michelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Michelle, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrubaker, Leslie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGanz, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaripzanov, Ildar H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaripzanov, Ildar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaripzanov, Ildar, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHahn, Cynthia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 a